People are turning to education for entertainment, whether from online lectures, learning vacations or television, for the love of learning new things and to stay economically viable.Our ancient ancestors built the Library of Alexandria to gather the world’s knowledge, but smartphones turn every palm into a knowledge palace.As the amount of human-created information spirals ever higher, our ability to sift through it has not kept pace. Increasingly condensed specialization is one result.The free meditation class offered weekly at the Hammer Museum in Los Angeles is credited with starting a community-mindfulness trend among American institutions.Schools, museums and some entrepreneurial individuals are experimenting with ways to teach art techniques online.Schools that offer these programs aim at commuters and use billboards, radio and a variety of social and other digital marketing tools.Students pay $10 a month for unlimited access to Skillshare’s 1,000 courses, and 850,000 users are signed up with the service, the company said.The digital world is booming with resources to help people who want to become comic book professionals, learn the tools of the trade or improve their craft.Debt held by those 65 and older has risen significantly in recent years, but the load may be eased with careful planning or government aid, or through an employer.Classes offer the opportunity to continue education from the comfort of home, but they can restrict the chance to build in-person social connections.